descriptionMd:
Created for Kernel Magazine’s 4th issue launch party, participants exchange their lock screens randomly to adopt a part of someone else's daily digital existence for the day.
&nbsp;
Meanwhile, all submitted lock screens are continuously used to create a communal photomontage of the 4th issue's cover.
&nbsp;
In addition to a fun icebreaker, the exercise encourages learning about someone from their digital residue: what do they pay attention to or want to hold onto? And how can our unique individual data become a cohesive collective artifact?
&nbsp;
I’m curious to explore other variants of this.. what if we could exchange our desktops, browser tabs, home screens, etc. for the day? how can those pieces of digital residue form a collective portrait?
